## § 5. Translation, convolution, and group-invariant operators

We now bring in dynamics: what operators does the character basis diagonalize? We need three definitions.

### The translation operator

For each $g \in G$, the **translation operator** $L_g$ acts on functions $f: G \to \mathbb{C}$ by

$$(L_g f)(x) := f(g^{-1} x).$$

The inverse in the definition is not a typo — it is forced by the requirement that translation be a group *action*, meaning that composing two translations should equal translation by the group product:

$$L_a (L_b f)(x) = (L_b f)(a^{-1} x) = f(b^{-1} a^{-1} x) = f((ab)^{-1} x) = (L_{ab} f)(x).$$

If we had defined $(L_g f)(x) = f(gx)$, we would have gotten $L_a L_b = L_{ba}$ — a right action, not a left action. Neither is wrong, but the sign convention has to be chosen once and stuck to. We use the left convention throughout.

Concretely:

- For $G = \mathbb{Z}_N$: $(L_k f)(n) = f(n - k)$. The signal shifts $k$ steps to the right.
- For $G = (\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$: $(L_u f)(v) = f(v \oplus u)$. (Since $u^{-1} = u$ in $(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$, the sign doesn't visibly matter here, but it is the same rule.)

### Group-invariant operators

A linear operator $T: V \to V$ is **group-invariant** if it commutes with translation:

$$T \circ L_g = L_g \circ T \qquad \text{for every } g \in G.$$

In signal processing language: $T$ commutes with shift. If the input is delayed by $g$, the output is delayed by the same amount, with no other change. For $G = \mathbb{Z}_N$, this is a **Linear Time-Invariant (LTI) system**. For $G = (\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$, it is a system invariant under XOR-shift of coordinates.

### Convolution as the archetypal group-invariant operator

We want to understand what a group-invariant operator on $V$ looks like in concrete terms. Any linear operator $T$ on $V$ is described by a matrix. Since $V$ has dimension $|G|$, this is a $|G| \times |G|$ matrix. It is convenient to label its rows and columns by group elements rather than by integer indices, so that the matrix entry $T_{x, y}$ tells us how strongly the input value at position $y$ contributes to the output value at position $x$:

$$(T f)(x) = \sum_{y \in G} T_{x, y} \, f(y).$$

For a completely general $T$, this matrix has $|G|^2$ independent entries — one per pair $(x, y)$. Group-invariance drastically cuts down that freedom by tying entries at different positions together.

<details class="orthogonal-disclosure" data-tone="derivation" markdown="1">
<summary class="orthogonal-disclosure__summary">Derive why translation invariance forces convolution</summary>

Concretely, "$T$ commutes with translation" means $L_g \circ T = T \circ L_g$ for every $g \in G$. Reading this out on the entry level: on the left, $(L_g \circ T) f$ applied at $x$ is the same as $T f$ applied at $g^{-1} x$, which as a sum against $f$ picks up the row $T_{g^{-1} x, \cdot}$. On the right, $(T \circ L_g) f$ applied at $x$ is $\sum_y T_{x, y} f(g^{-1} y)$, which after relabelling $y \to g y$ inside the sum becomes $\sum_y T_{x, g y} f(y)$. Equating for all $f$ gives

$$T_{g^{-1} x, \, y} = T_{x, \, g y} \qquad \text{for all } g, x, y.$$

This says something clean: the matrix entry is preserved when we simultaneously shift both indices by the same group element. If we translate the row index left by $g^{-1}$ and the column index left by $g^{-1}$, we hit the same entry. The entry $T_{x, y}$ therefore cannot depend on $x$ and $y$ independently; it can depend only on what remains after we quotient out by simultaneous translation, which is the "offset" of the pair — the group element $y^{-1} x$ that takes $y$ to $x$ under left multiplication.

To make this useful, name the offset dependence. Set

$$h(g) := T_{g, e},$$

which reads off the operator's matrix entry in the row indexed by $g$ and the column indexed by the identity $e$. Applied to any other pair $(x, y)$, we can slide both indices by $y^{-1}$ (using the translation-invariance we just proved) and get

$$T_{x, y} = T_{y^{-1} x, \, y^{-1} y} = T_{y^{-1} x, \, e} = h(y^{-1} x).$$

So every matrix entry is completely determined by the single function $h: G \to \mathbb{C}$. Substituting back into the operator formula,

$$(T f)(x) = \sum_{y \in G} f(y) \, h(y^{-1} x).$$

This sum is what we call **group convolution** of $f$ against $h$, and we write it $(f * h)(x)$.

</details>

Two names for the function $h$ are worth pinning down. The linear-algebra name is **kernel**: any expression of a linear operator as a sum or integral with a coefficient function has that coefficient function called the kernel of the operator. It is the same word used in "integral kernel" — where an operator $T f(x) = \int K(x, y) f(y) \, dy$ acting on functions of a continuous variable is fixed by specifying the two-variable weight function $K(x, y)$, and $K$ is called the operator's kernel. Our function $h(y^{-1} x)$ plays the same role, with the special structure that it depends on $x, y$ only through the offset $y^{-1} x$.

The signal-processing name for the same object is **impulse response**: $h(x)$ is the output the operator produces at position $x$ when the input is a single unit spike at the identity — that is, the delta function $\delta_e$ concentrated at $e$. The equivalence of the two names is immediate:

$$(T \delta_e)(x) = \sum_y \delta_e(y) \, h(y^{-1} x) = h(e^{-1} x) = h(x).$$

Feeding a unit spike into $T$ produces exactly the function $h$ as output. So the "kernel" and "impulse response" of a group-invariant operator are the same function, given two different names by two different traditions.

The correspondence goes both ways. Any function $h: G \to \mathbb{C}$ we write down defines a group-invariant operator via $(f * h)(x) = \sum_y f(y) h(y^{-1} x)$: direct calculation confirms this new operator commutes with every translation. And any group-invariant operator, as we showed above, arises from a unique $h$. So there is a one-to-one correspondence between group-invariant operators on $V$ and functions $h$ on $G$.

The upshot for what follows: "understand every operator that commutes with translation" and "understand convolution against every possible kernel $h$" are the same problem. When § 6 shows that characters diagonalize every group-invariant operator, that will simultaneously mean the characters diagonalize every convolution.

### The complexity problem

Convolution as written is expensive: for a signal of length $N = |G|$, computing all $N$ output values by the direct sum takes $N^2$ multiplications and additions. This is why unstructured convolution — a length-$10^6$ signal filtered by a length-$10^6$ kernel — is a computational catastrophe. The point of the character basis, developed next, is that this collapses to $O(N \log N)$.

