## § 8. The dyadic group $(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$ and the Walsh–Hadamard transform

Set $G = (\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$: the group of length-$n$ binary vectors under bitwise XOR. The group has order $N = 2^n$, and every element is its own inverse: $v \oplus v = 0$.

### Building characters from scratch, one bit at a time

Start with the simplest case, $n = 1$: the group $\mathbb{Z}_2$ has two elements $\{0, 1\}$. A character $\phi: \mathbb{Z}_2 \to \mathbb{C}^*$ must satisfy the homomorphism identity $\phi(a \oplus b) = \phi(a) \phi(b)$. Setting $a = b$ and using $a \oplus a = 0$:

$$\phi(0) = \phi(a)^2.$$

Since $0$ is the identity, $\phi(0) = 1$, so $\phi(a)^2 = 1$: the character output is a square root of unity, which in $\mathbb{C}$ leaves only $\pm 1$. There are therefore exactly two characters of $\mathbb{Z}_2$:

$$\chi_0(a) = 1, \qquad \chi_1(a) = (-1)^a.$$

The first is the trivial character; the second is the nontrivial one that distinguishes $0$ from $1$.

### Extending to $n$ bits

The group $(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$ is the direct product $\mathbb{Z}_2 \times \cdots \times \mathbb{Z}_2$ ($n$ times). Characters of a direct product are products of characters of the factors, so every character of $(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$ has the form

$$\chi_u(v) = \prod_{i=0}^{n-1} \chi_{u_i}(v_i) = \prod_{i=0}^{n-1} (-1)^{u_i v_i} = (-1)^{u \cdot v},$$

where $u \in (\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$ is a "mask" selecting which bits of $v$ contribute, and $u \cdot v = \sum_i u_i v_i \pmod 2$ is the parity of the bitwise AND. There are $2^n = N$ such $u$'s, giving $N$ characters — matching the dimension of $V$.

The character basis change is

$$\widehat{x}_u = \sum_{v \in (\mathbb{Z}_2)^n} x_v \, (-1)^{u \cdot v}.$$

This is the **Walsh–Hadamard Transform**. The change-of-basis matrix has entries $H_{u,v} = (-1)^{u \cdot v} \in \{+1, -1\}$; it is the **Hadamard matrix** of order $N$.

### The Hadamard matrix is real and symmetric

Because $\chi_u(v)$ is real ($= \pm 1$), the Hadamard matrix has no complex entries. Because $u \cdot v = v \cdot u$, it is symmetric. Both properties are specific to the dyadic group; the DFT matrix is complex and only Hermitian, not symmetric.

Answering an earlier open question: **the character of the Sylvester–Hadamard transform** is the function $\chi_u(v) = (-1)^{u \cdot v}$. It is a real-valued analogue of the Fourier character $e^{2\pi i k n / N}$, with the complex root of unity replaced by the real square root of unity $-1$. Concretely: for a signal indexed by bit strings (an image indexed by pixel coordinates written in binary; a Boolean function on $n$ variables; a vector of $2^n$ possible states of a $n$-bit register), the WHT is the natural spectral decomposition, and its "frequencies" are the $2^n$ possible parity-mask vectors $u$.

### Orthogonality, recovered from § 4

We do not need a separate proof. Since $\chi_u(v) = (-1)^{u \cdot v}$ is a character of the finite abelian group $(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$, § 4 immediately gives

$$\sum_{v} \chi_u(v) \overline{\chi_{u'}(v)} = \sum_{v} (-1)^{u \cdot v} \cdot (-1)^{u' \cdot v} = \sum_v (-1)^{(u \oplus u') \cdot v} = \begin{cases} N & \text{if } u = u', \\ 0 & \text{otherwise.} \end{cases}$$

The identity $\overline{(-1)^{u' \cdot v}} = (-1)^{u' \cdot v}$ used the real-valuedness, and $(-1)^a (-1)^b = (-1)^{a \oplus b}$ collapsed the exponents. (The vanishing of $\sum_v (-1)^{d \cdot v}$ for $d \neq 0$: pick any bit $j$ where $d_j = 1$; pair off each $v$ with $v \oplus e_j$; the two exponents differ by exactly $1$ mod $2$, so the two terms cancel. Half the sum plus its negative is zero.)

