## § 10. Fast algorithms from subgroup structure: the FFT parallel

The FWHT factorization is one instance of a general phenomenon: fast transforms exist for a group $G$ whenever $G$ has a chain of subgroups you can quotient down. For $(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$, the chain is

$$(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n \supset (\mathbb{Z}_2)^{n-1} \supset \cdots \supset \mathbb{Z}_2 \supset \{0\},$$

each step dividing the group order by $2$. The Sylvester factorization is this chain made concrete.

### The FFT is the same idea for $\mathbb{Z}_N$

For $G = \mathbb{Z}_N$ with $N = 2^n$, we have the chain

$$\mathbb{Z}_N \supset 2\mathbb{Z}_N \supset 4\mathbb{Z}_N \supset \cdots \supset \{0\}.$$

The Cooley–Tukey radix-2 algorithm exploits this chain. The idea is to split a length-$N$ signal by even and odd indices, DFT each half separately, and stitch. We need to figure out what "stitch" costs, and specifically why an extra set of complex phase factors — the twiddle factors — appears in the process.

<details class="orthogonal-disclosure" data-tone="derivation" markdown="1">
<summary class="orthogonal-disclosure__summary">Derive the radix-2 butterfly and its twiddle factor</summary>

Let $\omega_N = e^{2 \pi i / N}$ and compute the length-$N$ DFT of $x$ at frequency $k$, splitting the sum by the parity of the index:

$$X_k = \sum_{n=0}^{N-1} x_n \omega_N^{k n} = \sum_{m=0}^{N/2 - 1} x_{2m} \omega_N^{k \cdot 2m} + \sum_{m=0}^{N/2 - 1} x_{2m+1} \omega_N^{k(2m+1)}.$$

For the even-indexed sum, $\omega_N^{k \cdot 2m} = \omega_{N/2}^{k m}$ (a length-$N/2$ character), so the sum is exactly the length-$N/2$ DFT of the even samples evaluated at frequency $k$; call it $E_k$. The odd-indexed sum has one extra power of $\omega_N^k$ that can be pulled out:

$$\sum_m x_{2m+1} \omega_N^{k(2m+1)} = \omega_N^k \sum_m x_{2m+1} \omega_{N/2}^{k m} = \omega_N^k O_k,$$

where $O_k$ is the length-$N/2$ DFT of the odd-indexed samples. Combining and using $\omega_N^{k + N/2} = -\omega_N^k$:

$$X_k = E_k + \omega_N^k O_k, \qquad X_{k + N/2} = E_k - \omega_N^k O_k.$$

The factor $\omega_N^k$ multiplying $O_k$ is the **twiddle factor**.

</details> It arises because the odd-indexed samples sit at physical positions offset by $1$ from the even-indexed sublattice, and that offset shows up as a phase rotation in the frequency domain. Different frequencies $k$ pick up different phase rotations, so we get a whole diagonal matrix of twiddle factors $D_N = \operatorname{diag}(1, \omega_N, \omega_N^2, \ldots, \omega_N^{N/2 - 1})$ rather than a single scalar. Packaging the split, the DFT-of-length-$2N$ matrix factors as

$$F_{2N} = \begin{bmatrix} I_N & D_N \\ I_N & -D_N \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} F_N & 0 \\ 0 & F_N \end{bmatrix} P,$$

where $F_N$ is the length-$N$ DFT matrix and $P$ is the permutation that puts the even indices first and odd indices second.

Compare with the FWHT recursion:

$$H_{2N} = \begin{bmatrix} I_N & I_N \\ I_N & -I_N \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} H_N & 0 \\ 0 & H_N \end{bmatrix}.$$

The two recursions are structurally identical. The only difference is that the FFT twiddle matrix $D_N$ is a nontrivial diagonal of complex roots of unity, while the FWHT "twiddle" is just $I_N$. This reflects the different exponentials being used:

- FFT (from $\mathbb{Z}_N$): character generator is $\omega = e^{2\pi i / N}$, a nontrivial $N$-th root of unity.
- FWHT (from $(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$): character generator is $-1$, the trivial second root of unity.

The FWHT is the "clean corner" of the FFT family where the twiddle factors reduce to $\pm 1$. Everything else — that the transform is real, that no complex multiplications are needed, that the butterfly is just addition and subtraction — is a consequence of $-1$ being real.

### General mixed-radix and CRT

For $\mathbb{Z}_N$ with $N = N_1 N_2$ where $\gcd(N_1, N_2) = 1$, the Chinese Remainder Theorem gives $\mathbb{Z}_N \cong \mathbb{Z}_{N_1} \times \mathbb{Z}_{N_2}$, and the DFT factors into a Kronecker product of smaller DFTs. This is the **prime-factor FFT**. It runs faster than radix-2 when $N$ has small coprime factors, because there are no cross-factor twiddle factors at all (the isomorphism handles the coordinate translation exactly). Radix-2 handles the case where you cannot split into coprime pieces, at the cost of paying the twiddle multiplications.

The upshot: the same subgroup-decomposition idea powers both the FFT and the FWHT. The FWHT is faster per stage because the group $(\mathbb{Z}_2)^n$ decomposes into fully independent $\mathbb{Z}_2$ factors — no residual twiddle interaction between stages.

