## § 14. What we needed, and what we didn't: setting up Sturm–Liouville

Everything so far required three ingredients: (i) a finite group $G$, (ii) a linear operator commuting with translation by $G$, (iii) the standard inner product on $\mathbb{C}^{|G|}$. Given these, characters emerged as a basis that diagonalized every group-invariant operator.

What breaks if we relax "finite" to "continuous"? Two things happen. First, the sum $\sum_{g \in G}$ becomes an integral, so we need integrability and function-space technicalities. Second, if $G = \mathbb{R}$, we have to derive what the characters are. A continuous homomorphism $\chi: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{C}^*$ satisfies $\chi(t + s) = \chi(t) \chi(s)$; differentiating with respect to $s$ at $s = 0$ gives $\chi'(t) = \chi(t) \chi'(0)$, an ODE whose solution is $\chi(t) = e^{a t}$ with $a = \chi'(0) \in \mathbb{C}$. For $\chi$ to be unitary — take values on the unit circle, as characters must if orthogonality is to work — we need $|e^{a t}| = 1$ for all real $t$, forcing $a$ to be purely imaginary: $a = i\omega$ for some $\omega \in \mathbb{R}$. So the characters of $\mathbb{R}$ are $\chi_\omega(t) = e^{i\omega t}$, parameterized by a real frequency $\omega$. The dual group is again $\mathbb{R}$, with pairing $(t, \omega) \mapsto e^{i\omega t}$ playing the role $e^{2 \pi i k n / N}$ played in the finite case. However, these characters are not square-integrable — $\int_{-\infty}^\infty |e^{i \omega t}|^2 dt = \infty$ — so they don't sit inside $L^2(\mathbb{R})$; rigorous treatment of the Fourier transform on $\mathbb{R}$ requires distributions or Plancherel-style limiting procedures.

More interesting: what happens when we do not have a group at all, but do have a self-adjoint differential operator? The typical setup: a domain $[a, b] \subset \mathbb{R}$, a function space of $f: [a, b] \to \mathbb{C}$ with boundary conditions, and a linear differential operator $L$ with the property that $\langle Lf, h \rangle = \langle f, Lh \rangle$ for all $f, h$ meeting the boundary conditions. Under mild conditions, such an operator has a discrete orthogonal basis of eigenfunctions, and any operator that commutes with $L$ is diagonalized in that basis.

The Sturm–Liouville framework is what makes this concrete.

### The Sturm–Liouville form

A **Sturm–Liouville problem** is an eigenvalue equation of the form

$$L y := -\frac{d}{dt}\left[ p(t) \frac{dy}{dt} \right] + q(t) y = \lambda w(t) y,$$

on an interval $[a, b]$, with $p, q, w$ specified real-valued functions ($p > 0$ and $w > 0$ in the interior), and boundary conditions on $y(a), y(b)$. Different choices of $p, q, w$ and interval give different classical function bases.

### Why this specific form: integration by parts, twice

The eigenvalue equation is $Ly = \lambda w y$, or equivalently $Ly / w = \lambda y$. To make this a genuine self-adjoint eigenvalue problem, we need the operator $L / w$ to be self-adjoint under *some* inner product. The right inner product turns out to be the weighted one

$$\langle f, h \rangle_w := \int_a^b f(t) \overline{h(t)} \, w(t) \, dt.$$

The role of $w$ is to cancel itself: $\langle (L/w) f, h \rangle_w = \int (Lf/w) \overline{h} \, w \, dt = \int Lf \, \overline{h} \, dt$, which is the *unweighted* pairing of $Lf$ against $h$. So $L/w$ is self-adjoint under $\langle \cdot, \cdot \rangle_w$ if and only if $L$ is self-adjoint under the unweighted $\int f \overline{h} \, dt$. This is what we check.

<details class="orthogonal-disclosure" data-tone="proof" markdown="1">
<summary class="orthogonal-disclosure__summary">Why the Sturm–Liouville operator is self-adjoint</summary>

Apply integration by parts to $\int (Lf) \overline{h} \, dt$. The $qf \overline{h}$ term is already symmetric in $(f, \overline{h})$ and needs no work. The interesting term is $-\int (pf')' \overline{h} \, dt$:

$$-\int_a^b (pf')' \, \overline{h} \, dt = -\left[ pf' \overline{h} \right]_a^b + \int_a^b pf' \, \overline{h}' \, dt.$$

Apply integration by parts a second time to the remaining integral:

$$\int_a^b pf' \, \overline{h}' \, dt = \left[ pf \, \overline{h}' \right]_a^b - \int_a^b f \, \overline{(ph')'} \, dt.$$

Combining and cleaning up:

$$\int_a^b (Lf) \overline{h} \, dt = \left[ p (f \overline{h}' - f' \overline{h}) \right]_a^b + \int_a^b f \, \overline{(Lh)} \, dt.$$

If the boundary term $[p(f\overline{h}' - f'\overline{h})]_a^b$ vanishes (the job of the boundary conditions), then $\int (Lf) \overline{h} = \int f \overline{Lh}$: $L$ is self-adjoint under the unweighted inner product, so $L / w$ is self-adjoint under the weighted one. Standard spectral theory then guarantees:

- Eigenvalues $\lambda_n$ are real.
- Eigenfunctions for distinct eigenvalues are orthogonal in $\langle \cdot, \cdot \rangle_w$.
- The eigenfunctions form a complete basis of $L^2([a, b], w \, dt)$.

The nesting of $p$ inside the outer derivative is exactly what enabled the two-step integration by parts to close into a symmetric form.

</details> The isolation of $w$ on the right of $Ly = \lambda w y$ is exactly what makes the eigenvalue problem canonical after dividing through. Neither is arbitrary: they are the unique arrangement in which a second-order linear operator becomes a symmetric operator on a weighted function space.

### The general form

Every second-order linear ODE $A(t) y'' + B(t) y' + C(t) y = \lambda D(t) y$ can be converted to SL form by choosing an **integrating factor** $\mu(t)$ that groups the $y''$ and $y'$ terms into a single total derivative. Concretely, we want to find $\mu$ such that

$$\mu A \, y'' + \mu B \, y' = (\mu A \cdot y')' = \mu A \, y'' + (\mu A)' \, y'.$$

Matching the $y'$ coefficients requires $\mu B = (\mu A)' = \mu' A + \mu A'$, i.e.

$$\frac{\mu'}{\mu} = \frac{B - A'}{A} \quad \Longrightarrow \quad \mu(t) = \exp\left( \int \frac{B(t) - A'(t)}{A(t)} \, dt \right).$$

Applying this $\mu$ to the original ODE and identifying terms, we read off $p(t) = \mu(t) A(t)$, $q(t) = -\mu(t) C(t)$, and $w(t) = \mu(t) D(t)$. This recipe is why every classical named ODE (Bessel's, Legendre's, Chebyshev's, Hermite's) fits inside the SL framework: each has a specific $A, B, C, D$, and this integrating factor pins down the weight $w$ against which its solutions must be orthogonal.

