## § 16. The bridge: symmetry, self-adjointness, and non-abelian representations

The framework we developed for finite abelian groups (§ 1 – § 13) and the framework we used for Sturm–Liouville (§ 14 – § 15) look independent, but they are two views of the same underlying idea. This section sketches the unifying picture, which is the content of **representation theory of compact groups**.

### The general setup

Let $G$ be a group acting on a space $X$ (possibly continuous, possibly non-abelian), and let $L^2(X)$ be the space of square-integrable functions on $X$. The action of $G$ on $X$ induces an action on $L^2(X)$ by translation: $(L_g f)(x) = f(g^{-1} \cdot x)$. Any operator $T$ on $L^2(X)$ that commutes with this action (a $G$-equivariant operator) preserves each irreducible piece of the decomposition of $L^2(X)$ under $G$, and is therefore block-diagonalized by any basis that respects the irreducible decomposition.

For finite abelian $G$, irreducibles are 1-dimensional, and the basis is the characters (§ 3). For continuous non-abelian $G$, irreducibles can be higher-dimensional, but there is still a canonical decomposition. The **Peter–Weyl theorem** states this for compact groups: $L^2(G)$ decomposes as a direct sum over the irreducibles of $G$, with each irreducible contributing an orthogonal block whose basis is given by matrix coefficients of that irreducible.

The classical orthogonal functions of § 15 are exactly the matrix coefficients (or their diagonals) of specific irreducibles of specific groups.

### Trigonometric functions from $SO(2) \cong S^1$

The circle group $S^1$ is abelian and its characters are $\chi_k(\theta) = e^{i k \theta}$. These are the Fourier series basis. The equivalence with the SL derivation ($p = 1, q = 0, w = 1$, periodic boundary) is direct: the Laplacian $-d^2/d\theta^2$ commutes with rotation, so its eigenfunctions must be characters of $S^1$.

### Legendre polynomials from $SO(3)$

The rotation group of 3-space, $SO(3)$, is non-abelian. Its irreducible unitary representations have dimensions $1, 3, 5, 7, \ldots$ (odd numbers, one for each non-negative integer $\ell$). The 2ℓ+1 dimensional irrep acts on the space of degree-$\ell$ spherical harmonics $Y_\ell^m$ on the sphere. The Legendre polynomials $P_\ell(\cos\theta)$ are the "zonal" (i.e., axially symmetric) matrix coefficients — the $m = 0$ diagonal element of the $\ell$-th irrep, expressed as a function of the polar angle.

This is why Legendre polynomials appear in problems with rotational symmetry: they are the pieces of $L^2(S^2)$ that lie in the axially symmetric part of each $SO(3)$ irreducible. The SL equation and the rep-theory derivation both produce the same functions because they are asking the same question in different notations.

### Bessel functions from the Euclidean motion group $ISO(2)$

The group $ISO(2)$ consists of rigid motions of the plane (translations and rotations). It is non-abelian, non-compact, but its irreducible unitary representations are parameterized by a positive real number $k$ (the "radius" of the frequency). The matrix coefficients of the $k$-th irrep, taken between eigenstates of the rotation subgroup, are exactly the Bessel functions $J_\nu(k r)$.

This is why Bessel functions describe wave modes in cylindrically symmetric geometries: the wave equation in the plane commutes with $ISO(2)$, so its eigenmodes fall into the irreducibles of $ISO(2)$, whose radial matrix coefficients are Bessel functions.

### Chebyshev polynomials from $SU(2)$

The group $SU(2)$ consists of $2 \times 2$ complex matrices $g$ satisfying $g^\dagger g = I$ and $\det g = 1$. It is non-abelian and compact. It is closely related to $SO(3)$: every rotation of 3-space corresponds to two elements of $SU(2)$ (a matrix and its negative), which is why we get different representation-theoretic content from $SU(2)$ than from $SO(3)$.

<details class="orthogonal-disclosure" data-tone="derivation" markdown="1">
<summary class="orthogonal-disclosure__summary">Follow the SU(2) character calculation to the Chebyshev polynomials</summary>

Every element of $SU(2)$ is conjugate to some diagonal matrix

$$D_\theta = \begin{pmatrix} e^{i\theta} & 0 \\ 0 & e^{-i\theta} \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \theta \in [0, \pi]$$

(the angle $\theta$ is half the rotation angle of the corresponding element of $SO(3)$; the "conjugate to $D_\theta$" statement is just diagonalization). Since characters — traces of representations — are unchanged by conjugation, any character of any $SU(2)$ representation is a function of $\theta$ alone.

$SU(2)$ has one irreducible representation in each dimension $n = 1, 2, 3, \ldots$. Concretely, the $n$-dimensional irrep acts on homogeneous polynomials of degree $n - 1$ in two variables $(z_1, z_2)$: the element $D_\theta$ sends $z_1 \mapsto e^{i\theta} z_1$ and $z_2 \mapsto e^{-i\theta} z_2$, so it acts on the monomial $z_1^k z_2^{n-1-k}$ by multiplying it by $e^{i\theta(2k - (n-1))}$. The character (the trace of this action) is the sum over the $n$ monomials:

$$\chi_n(\theta) = \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} e^{i\theta(2k - (n-1))} = e^{-i\theta(n-1)} \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} e^{2i\theta k} = e^{-i\theta(n-1)} \cdot \frac{e^{2in\theta} - 1}{e^{2i\theta} - 1} = \frac{\sin(n\theta)}{\sin\theta}.$$

The function of $\theta$ on the right can be expanded (via repeated use of the identity $\sin((n+1)\theta) = 2 \cos\theta \sin(n\theta) - \sin((n-1)\theta)$) as a polynomial in $\cos\theta$ of degree $n-1$. That polynomial is called $U_{n-1}(\cos\theta)$, the **Chebyshev polynomial of the second kind**.

The first-kind Chebyshev polynomials $T_n$ arise from taking the *real part* of $e^{i n \theta}$ instead of the $\sin$-ratio. The eigenvalues of $D_\theta$ in the fundamental irrep are the two numbers $e^{i\theta}$ and $e^{-i\theta}$; their sum is $e^{i\theta} + e^{-i\theta} = 2\cos\theta$, and the sum of their $n$-th powers is

$$e^{in\theta} + e^{-in\theta} = 2\cos(n\theta) = 2 T_n(\cos\theta).$$

So both kinds of Chebyshev polynomials live inside the character theory of $SU(2)$: $U_{n-1}$ as the full character of the $n$-dimensional irrep, $T_n$ as (half) the trace of the $n$-th power of the fundamental.

</details> The trigonometric identity $T_n(\cos\theta) = \cos(n\theta)$ that made the Sturm–Liouville substitution work in § 15 is not a special feature of Chebyshev polynomials — it is the fact that these polynomials are literally sums of $e^{\pm i n \theta}$ evaluated at the eigenvalues of $D_\theta$, and $\theta$ is the natural coordinate on the circle of diagonal elements of $SU(2)$.

### The unified picture

The pattern across all cases is:

$$\text{Symmetry group} \;\;\longrightarrow\;\; \text{Irreducible representations} \;\;\longrightarrow\;\; \text{Orthogonal basis of } L^2.$$

- Symmetry finite abelian $\Rightarrow$ irreducibles are 1-dim $\Rightarrow$ basis is characters. Instances: DFT, WHT.
- Symmetry compact non-abelian $\Rightarrow$ irreducibles are higher-dim $\Rightarrow$ basis is matrix coefficients. Instances: Legendre, Chebyshev.
- Symmetry non-compact non-abelian $\Rightarrow$ irreducibles are infinite-dim, parameterized continuously $\Rightarrow$ basis is a continuous family of matrix coefficients. Instances: Bessel functions, continuous Fourier transform.

Sturm–Liouville is the "operator-first" way to arrive at these bases without naming the group: the self-adjoint operator $L$ encodes the symmetry, and its eigenfunctions turn out to be the same as what the group-theoretic construction produces. The two frameworks are complementary: rep theory says *why* these specific functions appear (the symmetry demands it); SL theory gives a concrete recipe to compute them (solve a specific ODE) without leaving the world of second-order differential equations. For all the specific bases we care about — Fourier, Walsh–Hadamard, Legendre, Chebyshev, Bessel — both frameworks apply, and both agree.

